er the parish apprenticeship system, women's work for poor law authorities and how it was taken into account by welfare systems, the changing nature of women's work, remuneration and technology in British agriculture, questionsof customary norms governing pay, female employment in many hitherto neglected urban industries, and women and the East India Company. The issues of gendered wages and customary earnings, family economies, regional and rural-urbancontrasts, the impact of technological change, and the links between female work and formal welfare systems, are raised throughout. Contributors STEVE HINDLE, JANE HUMPHRIES, STEVEN KING, PENELOPE LANE, NEIL RAVEN, MICHAEL ROBERTS, PAMELA SHARPE, K.D.M. SNELL, NICOLA VERDON, SAMANTHA WILLIAMS.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSex rolexHistoryzEngland. 0aWomenxEconomic conditionszEngland. 0aWomenxEmploymentxHistoryzEngland. 0aWomenxSocial conditionszEngland. 4aModern History. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Human Resources & Personnel Management.2bisacsh  afeminism.1 aHindle, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumphries, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLane, Penelope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLane, Penelope, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRaven, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaven, Neil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRoberts, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharpe, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSnell, K.D.M., econtributor.4ctb4